      "id": "/page/0/Text/9",
      "block_type": "Text",
      "html": "<p block-type=\"Text\">The down-and-in barrier option has a knock-in barrier level, which is below the initial underlying asset level. Before the maturity, if the underlying asset goes below the barrier level the barrier option will be knocked in and become a vanilla option. Otherwise, the barrier option will expire worthless at maturity. Down-and-in puts are more common in this case. Bearish investors can buy down-and-in puts and pay a lower premium than that on the vanilla put options.</p>",
